<!--
VOICING PLAN:
- Non-diatonic substitutions: Eb→Em(vi), A major→Am(ii), B major→Em context, C#°→Bm(iii),
  G7→G(I) or ignored (already diatonic), F#7→D(V), Bø7→Gm7(ii7), D major→C(V),
  F#m→Am(iii), FΔ7→F(I)
- I (F) voicings: F-C-F-A open with 3rd on top (3+3+3 "333" = IΔ pattern) in climax
- IV (Bb): Bb-F-Bb-D = "334" pattern (root oct with 3rd), used at climax m13 for maximum weight
- V (C): C-G-C-E = "433" pattern (sus4 + octave) for authoritative dominant
- ii (Gm): G-D-G-Bb = "334" gives full minor 7th color with Bb on top
- V7 (C7): C-G-E-Bb = spread 7th chord, all four note slots filled
- iii (Am): A-E-A = open quartal 3-note — keeps Am lighter than I

VOICE LEADING HIGHLIGHTS:
- Verse m3: I→iii→IV — bass descends F2→A2→Bb2 by 3rd then semitone (smooth)
- Chorus mm. 9-12: V→I oscillation with RH broken-chord arpeggio adds momentum
- V7 (C-G-E-Bb) has all four chord tones in spread register — maximum dissonance before I resolution
- m13 climax: LH Bb2-F3-Bb3-D4 spans a 10th — widest LH voicing in the piece

TEXTURE ARC:
- Verse 1 mm.1-8: 3-note LH, 2-note RH (lightest) with arpeggio coloring
- Chorus mm.9-12: 4-note LH at V7 and I; RH 3-note; broken chord momentum
- Bridge mm. 13-16: IV at 4-note LH climax (Bb-F-Bb-D), RH F-C-F5 at highest point
- Final mm. 17-20: ii and I alternate at 4-note LH; convergence to F root pos final chord
-->
